{"hits": {"hits": [{"created": "2026-01-09T00:41:35.749410+00:00", "modified": "2026-01-09T00:41:36.416956+00:00", "id": 18191310, "conceptrecid": "18191309", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.18191310", "conceptdoi": "10.5281/zenodo.18191309", "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.18191310", "metadata": {"title": "Mexico's island biosecurity programme: collaborative formulation and implementation", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.18191310", "publication_date": "2019", "description": "(Uploaded by Plazi for the IPBES Invasive Alien Species Assessment) Mexico's National Strategy on Invasive Species (2010) and the National Strategy for the Conservation and Sustainable Development of Islands (2012) embrace its steady and positive 20-year trajectory on island restoration. Mexico has come halfway to having all islands free of invasive mammals. To sustain these results in the long-term, biosecurity became a priority. To implement these national strategies, the National Commission for Knowledge and Use of Biodiversity (CONABIO) and the National Commission for Natural Protected Areas (CONANP) integrated a participatory programme to develop the country's capacities for managing invasive alien species (IAS). With funding from the Global Environment Facility (GEF) through the United Nations Development Programme (UNDP), and private donors, the IAS programme is now under operation. Grupo de Ecolog\u00eda y Conservaci\u00f3n de Islas, A.C. (GECI), a professional Mexican NGO, is implementing the programme on islands, along four lines of action: (1) island biosecurity; (2) environmental learning and capacity building; (3) control and eradication of IAS; and (4) monitoring to assess ecological recovery. While promoting the importance of biosecurity amongst all social actors, the focus is on long-term formal implementation, culture and everyday life. The methods therefore vary: workshops with authorities, integration of specific biosecurity protocols, and art and conservation activities with the local communities, particularly with children and young adults. The experience to date shows that enforcement by authorities and integration of the subject by local fishermen communities and island users are two key factors in sustaining the valuable and tangible results achieved to date over the long term.", "access_right": "restricted", "creators": [{"name": "Latofski-Robles, M.", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "M\u00e9ndez-S\u00e1nchez, F", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Aguirre-Mu\u00f1oz, A", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "J\u00e1uregui-Garc\u00eda, C", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Koleff-Osorio, P", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Gonz\u00e1lez-Mart\u00ednez, A I", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Born-Schmidt, G", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Bernal-Stoopen, J", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Rend\u00f3n-Hern\u00e1ndez, E", "affiliation": null}], "keywords": ["Chapter 5", "biodiversity", "environment assessment", "IPBES", "Alien Invasive Species Assessment AIS", "invasive species"], "related_identifiers": [{"identifier": "hash://md5/c908ea40ba3b9797189bd1d297e5847e", "relation": "hasVersion", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "hash://sha256/21fdce4ce649ac184ddf0f7837c9cbeaa6035df87534c1eed369d486a90ad109", "relation": "hasVersion", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "zotero://select/groups/2352922/items/XLWNY7YF", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "https://zotero.org/groups/2352922/items/XLWNY7YF", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "https://linker.bio/cut:hash://md5/05e65d42917641d1c37bf1a619bfc6bd!/b99289-101414", "relation": "isDerivedFrom", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "hash://md5/359bd494433933b868f85e88d3437f76", "relation": "isPartOf", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "10.5281/zenodo.7430682", "relation": "isCitedBy", "resource_type": "publication-report", "scheme": "doi"}, {"identifier": "10.5281/zenodo.1410543", "relation": "isCompiledBy", "resource_type": "software", "scheme": "doi"}], "